DAN_ORIGINAL = {
  "3": {
    "1": "<p><strong>tselem</strong> (<em>ṣelem</em>, Aramaic): image, statue. The same word used in Dan 2:31 for the statue in Nebuchadnezzar's dream — whose head was gold. Here Nebuchadnezzar makes an entire image of gold, apparently extending the gold-head glory to the whole statue. The dimension ratio (60 cubits tall, 6 cubits wide — roughly 90 × 9 feet) is unusually narrow; some commentators suggest a statue on a pedestal. The plain of Dura (<em>biqdath dura</em>, the plain of Dura) is unidentified but the name suggests a walled enclosure. The Babylonian setting is historically plausible: large royal cultic images are attested in Neo-Babylonian texts.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>rab-ravravan</strong> (<em>rab-rabrĕwān</em>): an honorific superlative — the most exalted leaders. The list in vv. 2-3 includes seven categories of Babylonian court officials (<em>satraps, prefects, governors, counselors, treasurers, justices, magistrates</em>). The sevenfold list is comprehensive — the whole administrative hierarchy is summoned. The political intent is total: Nebuchadnezzar wants universal imperial compliance with the dedication.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The repetition of the full official list from v. 2 in v. 3 is a deliberate literary device — the narrator emphasizes both the command and its compliance with the same catalogue. The phrase <strong>qamah letsel tsalma</strong> (<em>qāmāh leṣēl ṣalmāʾ</em>: stood before the image) uses the spatial verb <em>qum</em> (stand/arise) — they have physically placed themselves in the posture of deference before the image. The repetition creates the impression of mass, relentless pressure.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>qara</strong> (<em>qārēʾ</em>): the herald cried out. The Aramaic <em>karoz</em> (herald, v. 4) is a loanword from Persian <em>kāruza</em> or Greek <em>kēryx</em> — one of Daniel's Aramaic Persian/Greek loanwords that scholars note. The announcement formula (<em>lekhon amreen ammin umevaya uleshanaya</em>: &ldquo;to you it is commanded, peoples and nations and languages&rdquo;) uses the triadic nations-formula that appears throughout the book (2:44; 3:4; 4:1; 5:19; 6:25; 7:14) — every empire-spanning utterance in Daniel reaches all peoples, nations, and languages, the same universal formula the NT applies to Christ's dominion (Rev 5:9; 7:9).</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>nefila'</strong> (<em>nip̄lûn</em>, imperfect): you will fall and worship. The imperfect in Aramaic carries imperatival force here (a future-as-command). <strong>sagad</strong> (<em>sĕgid</em>): to prostrate oneself in worship — the technical term for cult-prostration throughout ch. 3, occurring eleven times in the chapter. The instruments listed (<em>qarna, mashroqita, qathros, sabbeka, psanterin, sumponeyya</em>) include a mix of Aramaic/Semitic and Greek loanwords (qathros = Greek <em>kithara</em>, harp; psanterin = Greek <em>psalterion</em>; sumponeyya = Greek <em>symphōnia</em>, bagpipes or harmony) — evidence of the Persian-Greek cultural milieu, exactly what would be expected in a sixth-fifth century Babylonian court.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>atun nura</strong> (<em>attûn nûrāʾ</em>): furnace of fire. The <em>atun</em> is a large smelting/burning furnace, likely a brick kiln similar to those used for the massive Babylonian building projects. The phrase <em>yaqidta</em> (burning hot) emphasizes intensity. The death penalty as immediate and public — without trial — is the political function of a cultic test: refusal is treated as sedition, not just impiety. The furnace as execution device is attested in ancient Near Eastern legal contexts (Jer 29:22 refers to Zedekiah's officials being roasted by Nebuchadnezzar).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The response of the entire assembly: <strong>sagad</strong> — they prostrated themselves and worshipped the image. The Aramaic construction <em>nefila sagdeen</em> (falling, worshipping) uses two simultaneous participles describing a single act: the physical prostration is the worship. The mass compliance of &ldquo;all the peoples, nations, and languages&rdquo; at the sound of music underscores the social pressure facing the three men — the entire world system bows. The counter-narrative of three men standing is Daniel's emphasis: faithful resistance against universal pressure.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>qeretsayyata</strong> (<em>qĕreṣayyāʾ</em>): they accused, or literally &ldquo;ate the pieces of&rdquo; — an idiom for slander/denunciation derived from the image of a predator consuming. The Chaldeans (<em>kasday</em>) are Babylon's elite priestly-scholarly class; their denunciation of the Jews is both political (they resent the Jews' elevation, cf. 2:49) and religious (they are the guardians of Babylonian cult). The phrase <em>kasday qeretsayyata yehudaya</em> (Chaldeans accused Jews) sets up the ethnic and religious conflict explicitly.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>malka lealam kheyey</strong> (<em>malkāʾ lĕʿālam ḥĕyay</em>): O king, live forever. This is the standard Babylonian/Persian court greeting formula. In Aramaic it uses the jussive-imperative: &ldquo;may you live forever.&rdquo; Its repetition at every royal appearance in Daniel (2:4; 3:9; 5:10; 6:6, 21) functions as a literary marker of the human court's pretension to divine permanence — a pretension YHWH consistently exposes in the book.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The accusers restate the king's decree verbatim: this is the narrative technique of exact citation to establish the legal precision of the charge. The decree is unambiguous — no escape clause for conscience or religion. The literary function is to make the three men's refusal fully deliberate: they know exactly what they are refusing. The precision of the charge also underscores the clarity of YHWH's vindication: if the accusation is exact, the deliverance is equally exact.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>man-hu alaha</strong> (<em>man hûʾ ʾĕlāhāʾ</em>): who is the god? — the rhetorical question embedded in the accusers' speech (<em>if they do not bow, they are to be thrown into the furnace</em>) sets the stage for the king's own version of the same question in v. 15. The Aramaic question-form with the emphatic <em>man</em> (who?) is used throughout Daniel for challenges to divine authority.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>la-ilu elahach pelachain</strong> (<em>lāʾ-ilāhāk pāleḥîn</em>): they are not serving your gods. The verb <em>pelach</em> is the Aramaic term for religious service/cult-service — used for both pagan worship and YHWH-service. The accusation is precisely the violation of cultic loyalty: the three men serve a different lord. The names Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego (<em>shadrak, meshak, aved-nego</em>) are Babylonian court names given in 1:7 to replace their Hebrew names — but their Hebrew loyalty persists behind the Babylonian veneer.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>ach birgaz u-chemah</strong> (<em>ʾeḏayin nebukhad-netstsar birgaz ûḥĕmāʾ</em>): then Nebuchadnezzar in rage and fury. The two synonyms for anger (<em>rigza</em> = rage/trembling, <em>chema</em> = hot anger/wrath) appear together for emphasis — the king's emotion is intense. Aramaic frequently uses paired synonyms for emphasis, particularly in court-speech. The repetition of his full name in the narrative context is also emphatic: the narrator does not abbreviate to &ldquo;the king.&rdquo;</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>hatsteva</strong> (<em>haṣṣĕḇāʾ</em>): Is it true? Or intentional? The Aramaic word can mean &ldquo;deliberate/on purpose.&rdquo; The king's question implies disbelief — he promoted these men (1:7; 2:49), and their defiance is personally offensive. The question form (<em>is it true</em>) before pronouncing judgment shows a vestige of due process, though the outcome is pre-decided by the rage of vv. 13, 19.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>man-hu alaha di yesheyzevinnkon mi-yadi</strong> (<em>man hûʾ ʾĕlāhāʾ dî yĕšêzĕvinnĕkôn mîyadî</em>): who is the god who will deliver you from my hand? This is the theological climax of the confrontation: Nebuchadnezzar's question is a direct challenge to YHWH's existence and power. The phrase <em>mi-yadi</em> (from my hand) echoes the Exodus language where Pharaoh asks &ldquo;who is YHWH that I should obey his voice?&rdquo; (Exod 5:2). The answer to both pharaoh and Nebuchadnezzar is the same: YHWH delivers his people from the hands of the most powerful rulers on earth.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>la khashcheen anan lehotava-k pethgam al-dena</strong> (<em>lāʾ-ḥaššĕḥîn ʾănaḥnāʾ lĕhātābāʾk pittĕgām ʿal-dĕnāh</em>): we have no need to answer you in this matter. The three men's response is remarkable in its confidence: <em>la khashchin</em> = we are not compelled/anxious. The root <em>khash</em> suggests urgency or need — they feel no urgency to defend themselves. The answer is not defiance but trust: the issue does not require their advocacy because YHWH is the one who will speak through the outcome.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>ithai elahana di anan palekheen yakhil leshezavah min-atun nura yaqidta</strong> (<em>ʾîṯay ʾĕlāhana dî ʾănaḥnāʾ pālĕḥîn yākil lĕšêzābāh min-ʾattûn nûrāʾ yāqiḏtāʾ</em>): if our God whom we serve is able to deliver us from the burning fiery furnace. The Aramaic conditional <em>hn ... ithai</em> (if there is) does not express doubt but marks the condition rhetorically; the real statement is the conviction of v. 18. <strong>yakhil</strong> (<em>yākil</em>): is able — the same root as the NT Greek <em>dunamai</em>. The ability of YHWH is affirmed even while acknowledging that deliverance is not guaranteed on human terms.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>v'hen la yedaʿ leh malka di le-ilahacha la felechin vli-tselem dahava la sagdeen</strong> (<em>wĕhin lāʾ yĕḏaʿ leh malkāʾ dî lēʾ-ʾĕlāhāk lāʾ pāleḥîn</em>): and if not — be it known to you, O king, that we will not serve your gods or worship the golden image. The unconditional confession: <em>v'hen la</em> (and if not) — even if YHWH does not deliver us, we will not bow. This is the pivot of the entire narrative: the faith statement that does not make deliverance contingent on rescue. The theological depth is enormous: the three men trust YHWH not because he will certainly rescue them but because he is YHWH. This is the same unconditional faith as Job 13:15 (<em>though he slay me, yet will I trust in him</em>).</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>hash-tannei tsvey anpoh</strong> (<em>ḥaš-tannê ṣĕwê ʾanpôhi</em>): the form of his face was changed — literally <em>changed the appearance of his face</em>. The Aramaic <em>shannei</em> means to change/alter; the noun <em>tsevah</em> (form/color) is related to the word for color or appearance. The furnace temperature is increased sevenfold — a hyperbolic number expressing extreme intensification. The literary structure mirrors the defiance: the three men refused to bend; the king bends the furnace temperature. Human extremity only sets up divine demonstration.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>gibbare chayil</strong> (<em>gibbārê ḥayil</em>): mighty men of valor. The superlative construction uses the noun <em>gibbar</em> (warrior, mighty one) with <em>chayil</em> (strength, wealth, army) — the most elite soldiers available. That these are the very men who are killed by the flame while throwing the three into the furnace (v. 22) is an ironic reversal: human power is destroyed by its own instrument of execution; those it kills are unharmed.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Bound in their clothing: <strong>sarbalehon patishehon vekarbaltehon</strong> — the list of garments includes several Persian loanwords (<em>sarbel</em> = tunic, <em>patish</em> = possibly a garment or mantle, <em>karbela</em> = perhaps a cap or head covering). The detail that they were thrown in fully clothed — no stripping, no preparation — makes the subsequent observation (&ldquo;not even their clothing smelled of fire,&rdquo; v. 27) more remarkable. The binding (<em>kefitu</em>, bound/tied) emphasizes helplessness: they are thrown helpless and fully clothed into the furnace.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>gevurta malka yaqidat</strong> (<em>giḇûrtāʾ malkāʾ yaqiḏat</em>): the king's command was urgent/fierce. The root <em>geburat</em> (might, fierceness) is related to <em>gibbar</em> (warrior) — the same word used for the mighty men of v. 20. The irony is complete: the king's mighty command kills his own mighty men while the unarmed prisoners walk free. The causal structure — because the king's command was fierce — is the narrator's way of saying that human extremity of power is self-destructive.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The three men fell bound into the midst of the burning furnace. The Aramaic <em>naflu</em> (they fell) is the same verb root as the &ldquo;falling down to worship&rdquo; demanded of all peoples (vv. 5-7). The three men who refused to fall in worship of the image are now literally fallen into the furnace — the irony of position. They fall not in worship but in faith, into the fire that will not harm them.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>etdahar malka</strong> (<em>ʾeṯdahar malkāʾ</em>): the king was alarmed, startled. The root <em>dahar</em> means to terrify, to disturb greatly. The king arose in haste (<em>behitbehala</em>) — the same root as the &ldquo;haste&rdquo; of frightened men throughout Daniel (4:5; 5:9). His question — &ldquo;did we not throw three men bound into the fire?&rdquo; — is forensically careful before he announces the vision of four men walking in the fire.</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>bar-elaheen</strong> (<em>bar-ʾĕlāhîn</em>): son of the gods. The plural <em>elaheen</em> (gods) reflects Nebuchadnezzar's polytheistic frame: he sees the fourth figure as a divine being, one of the <em>elaheen</em>. The singular <em>bar</em> (son of) individualizes the being: not a generic divine, but one specific divine figure. Christian readers have traditionally seen a Christophany here — the pre-incarnate Son appearing in the fire with his servants. The ambiguity between <em>ben-elahim</em> (son of God) and <em>bar-elaheen</em> (son of the gods) is theologically rich: Nebuchadnezzar can only name what he sees in his frame; the narrative's deeper meaning exceeds his frame.</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>avdohi di-el-ilai</strong> (<em>ʿabdôhî dî-ʾēl-ʿelyāʾ</em>): servants of the Most High God. Nebuchadnezzar calls them out using the divine title <em>el-ilai</em> (God Most High) — the superlative form of <em>ilai</em> (high/exalted). The title appears frequently in Daniel for YHWH (2:18, 19, 20, 37, 44; 3:26, 32; 4:2, 17, 24, 25, 32, 34; 5:18, 21; 7:18, 22, 25, 27; 11:36). The Gentile king's use of <em>el-ilai</em> is itself a form of acknowledgment: whatever the fourth figure was, YHWH is the Most High whose servants he was protecting.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The verification of the miracle by the assembled officials: <strong>la shelet nura begeshmeehon</strong> (<em>lāʾ šĕleṭ nûrāʾ begiš-mêhôn</em>): fire had no power over their bodies. <em>Shelet</em> (had power/authority) is a key word in Daniel — the same root used for those who have dominion, authority, power. Fire's authority is denied: it could not exercise its jurisdiction over YHWH's servants. The four specific statements (&ldquo;not singed, garments unchanged, no smell of fire&rdquo;) are legally precise testimony — a formal verification of the miracle.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>malʾakheh</strong> (<em>malʾakhêhî</em>): his angel. Nebuchadnezzar now identifies the fourth figure as YHWH's angel rather than a generic divine being — a shift from <em>bar-elaheen</em> (son of the gods) to <em>malʾakheh</em> (his angel/messenger). The verb <em>sheziv</em> (delivered) is the same root used by the three men in their declaration (v. 17: <em>yakhil leshezavah</em> — able to deliver). YHWH did exactly what they said he could do. <em>Shenet pitgam malka</em> (changed the king's word) — the king's decree was not annulled but made irrelevant: the fire obeyed YHWH, not the king.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Nebuchadnezzar's decree protecting the servants of YHWH: <strong>umeshta</strong> (<em>ûmešnāʾ</em>: to be dismembered) and <strong>baitehhon nevali yishtavon</strong> (their houses to be made a dunghill). The punishment for blasphemy against YHWH is given in terms of the standard Babylonian execution-and-property-confiscation formula. The Aramaic <em>negida</em> (decree/ruling) is a royal edict with universal force. Notably, Nebuchadnezzar does not convert: he issues a decree of toleration, not a confession of monotheism.</p>",
    "30": "<p><strong>tzalach</strong> (<em>ṣĕlaḥ</em>): promoted/prospered. The verb root <em>tsalach</em> means to advance, prosper, or progress — used in Ezra 5-6 for the progress of the temple-building. The three men are promoted (<em>harbit</em> = advanced to greater status) in the province of Babylon. The narrative ends with worldly vindication — the same pattern as Daniel himself in ch. 2: faithfulness leads to promotion. The literary structure is chiastic: forced to appear before the king (v. 13) → thrown into furnace → vindicated and promoted before the king (v. 30).</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p><strong>nebukhad-netstsar malka lekhol-amaya umevaya ulishanaya</strong> (<em>nĕḇûḵad-neṣṣar malkāʾ lĕḵol-ʿammayyāʾ ûmĕʾayyāʾ wĕliššānayyāʾ</em>): Nebuchadnezzar the king to all peoples, nations, and languages. Chapter 4 is unique in Scripture: a Gentile king's first-person testimony and praise of YHWH, framed as a royal letter to the whole empire. The Aramaic word <em>shelamkhon yisgeh</em> (may your peace increase) echoes the standard greeting of royal Aramaic letters (identical to the Elephantine papyri and Ezra's correspondence). The literary form authenticates the setting.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>atayya v'timhaya</strong> (<em>ʾāṯayyāʾ wĕṯimhāyyāʾ</em>): signs and wonders. The Aramaic pair is the standard formula for divine acts of power — used consistently in Daniel (6:27-28) and paralleled in Acts 2:22 for Christ's mighty works. <em>Shaphir qadamai</em> (it is a good thing before me): the king judges that his testimony is worthy — a self-aware editorial note from the narrator (Nebuchadnezzar speaking as if from a position of restored sanity and faith).</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>malkhuteh malkhut alam</strong> (<em>malkûṯêh malkûṯ ʿālam</em>): his kingdom is an everlasting kingdom. The Aramaic <em>alam</em> (world/eternity) is cognate to the Hebrew <em>olam</em>. This confession in v. 3 is repeated almost verbatim in v. 34 after Nebuchadnezzar's humiliation — it frames the chapter: the king knows the truth before his madness and confesses it again after. The phrase recurs at 7:14 for the Son of Man's dominion — the eternal kingdom language reaches its Christological fulfillment there.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>shale</strong> (<em>šĕlēh</em>): at ease, prospering, tranquil. The Aramaic root <em>shelah</em> (peace/security) describes Nebuchadnezzar's state before the vision. <em>Raʿnan</em> (flourishing/luxuriant) is a word normally applied to trees and plants — used here metaphorically of the king's prosperity, foreshadowing the tree-image of vv. 10-12. The dream comes in this moment of peak prosperity: the highest point of human achievement becomes the site of divine intervention.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>khezve de-yalbunani</strong> (<em>ḥĕzwê dî-yḇalʿunannî</em>): dreams that terrified me. The Aramaic root <em>bela</em> (swallow/terrify) is vivid — the dreams consumed him. <em>Dimyonaya al-mishkevi</em> (images upon my bed) uses the plural <em>dimyona</em> (imaginings/visions) for the frightening content. The juxtaposition of prosperity (v. 4) and terror (v. 5) is the narrative hinge: success does not protect from divine warning.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>belteshatzar rav kharshaya</strong> (<em>bēlṭĕšaṣṣar rab ḥarṭummayāʾ</em>): Belteshazzar, chief of the magicians. Daniel's Babylonian court name (<em>belteshatzar</em> = &ldquo;Bel protect his life&rdquo; or &ldquo;may Bel protect the king&rdquo;) is used by the narrator here in the king's speech — but the Aramaic adds <em>di-ruach elahim qadishim beh</em> (in whom is the spirit of the holy gods), the same formula the queen uses in 5:11. The court name conceals a Hebrew reality; the spirit-formula reveals it.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>v'acharon ul Daniel</strong> (<em>wĕʾaḥărîn ʿāl Dāniyyēʾl</em>): and finally Daniel came in. The detail that Daniel comes in last — after all the other wise men have failed — heightens his presentation as the one who alone has the spirit. The narrative echoes ch. 2: the wise men fail, Daniel succeeds. <em>Pesha</em> (interpretation) is the Aramaic technical term for dream-interpretation used throughout ch. 2 and 4-5.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>di-ruach elahim qadishim beh</strong> (<em>dî-rûaḥ ʾĕlāhîn qaddîšîn bēhî</em>): in whom is the spirit of the holy gods. The plural <em>elahim qadishim</em> (holy gods) again reflects the king's polytheistic frame, but his consistent use of this formula for Daniel suggests he has identified Daniel with a unique divine source. The same phrase appears in 5:11, 14 — it is the queen's formula and then the king's. The spirit that distinguishes Daniel from all others is YHWH's spirit, misidentified by the Babylonian frame as the spirit of &ldquo;holy gods&rdquo; (plural).</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>rav kharshaya</strong> (<em>rab ḥarṭummayāʾ</em>): master of the magicians. The Aramaic <em>chartom</em> (magician/diviner) is possibly an Egyptian loanword (<em>ḥr-tp</em> or similar) carried into the ANE court tradition. Nebuchadnezzar addresses Daniel as the superior of the court wisdom class — but then appeals to the spirit that transcends that class. The address <em>la ya'aqer manach raz</em> (no secret troubles you) establishes Daniel's competence before the request.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>ilana begoah shemayya</strong> (<em>ʾîlānāʾ begoah šemayyāʾ</em>): the tree in the middle of the earth / at the height of heaven. The dream-vision opens with the cosmic tree motif familiar from Mesopotamian iconography: a world-tree whose branches reach heaven, whose roots go deep. The Aramaic <em>ilana</em> (tree) appears seven times in vv. 10-23. The cosmic tree is a standard image for empire in ANE literature — cf. Ezek 31:3-9 (Assyria as cedars of Lebanon). The height reaching heaven (<em>rugbeh limshet lishemayya</em>) echoes the tower of Babel (<em>ve-rosho vashamayim</em>, Gen 11:4).</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>sgav ilana v'taqef</strong> (<em>sgā ʾîlānāʾ wetqēp̄</em>): the tree grew tall and became strong. The two verbs — <em>sga</em> (to grow large/magnify) and <em>tqep</em> (to become strong) — describe a progressive intensification. <em>Ad-shamayya</em> (to the heavens): Aramaic <em>shamayya</em> (the heavens) is the same word in Aramaic and Hebrew. The visibility clause — &ldquo;it was visible to the end of all the earth&rdquo; — is imperial hyperbole appropriate for a world-empire: what reaches to heaven is visible everywhere.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The tree providing food and shelter for all creatures: <strong>tepeh saggi</strong> (abundant fruit), <strong>meta lesavah lekhola</strong> (food for all). The tree as provider of food, shade, and shelter echoes the parable of the mustard seed (Matt 13:32) — a tree under which the birds of the air nest. The Babylonian tree-image (power as shelter) becomes in the NT the Christ-image (kingdom as shelter). The Aramaic detail that &ldquo;all flesh was fed from it&rdquo; (<em>kol-beshar yitnezuun minneh</em>) is universal — the tree feeds every living thing.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>ir v'qaddish</strong> (<em>ʿîr wĕqaddîš</em>): a watcher and a holy one. The <em>ir</em> (watcher/waking one) is an angelic being unique to Daniel in the canonical OT (though appearing in the Enoch literature). The term <em>iqad</em> (watcher/one who watches) suggests a heavenly being who observes and enforces divine decisions. Paired with <em>qaddish</em> (holy one), it is a doublet for a single angelic figure. The heavenly court language that dominates chs. 4-5 and 7 positions YHWH as the true king whose heavenly council issues binding decrees over human kingdoms.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>gadu ilana</strong> (<em>gûdû ʾîlānāʾ</em>): cut down the tree. The imperative <em>gadu</em> is from the root <em>geda</em> (to cut down) — the same verb used in the OT for felling trees (Deut 19:5). The watcher's decree is juridical: <em>badar periage</em> (scatter its fruit) — the reversal of the tree's provision. The stump is left with a band of iron and bronze: <em>ikar shorshohi b'ara</em> (leave its roots/stump in the earth) — a crucial detail that signals the judgment is not final elimination but temporary humiliation with restoration in view.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>ikar shorshohi</strong> (<em>ʾiqqar šorĕšôhî</em>): the stump of its roots. <em>Ikar</em> is the tree-stump — what remains after felling. The binding of the stump with iron and bronze (<em>be-essar di-parzel unechash</em>) prevents regrowth during the seven times. Then the pivotal pronoun shift: &ldquo;let his heart be changed from a man's, and let an animal's heart be given to him&rdquo; — the tree suddenly becomes the king. The Aramaic <em>levav anasha</em> (heart of a man) → <em>levav chaiva</em> (heart of an animal) describes the loss of rational dignity (<em>tselem elahim</em>, the image of God in human terms).</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>levav enasha yishnon mineh</strong> (<em>libbēhî min-ʾĕnāšāʾ yĕšannaʾ</em>): let his heart be changed from a man's. The verb <em>shanna</em> (to change/alter) was used in 3:28 for the angel who changed the king's fire-decree. Now it describes the reversal of rational faculty. <strong>levav chaiva yityhav leh</strong> (an animal's heart be given to him): the passive form (<em>yityhav</em> = let it be given) uses the divine passive — God is the implied agent. The number <em>shiv'a idanin</em> (seven times/seasons) uses the ambiguous <em>idan</em> — period, season, time — which may mean seven years or seven seasons.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>bigzerat iryin petagma uvammar qadishin shuʾleta</strong> (<em>bigĕzêrat ʿîrîn pittĕgāmāʾ ûbimēʾmar qaddîšîn šūʾaltāʾ</em>): by the decree of the watchers the sentence and by the word of the holy ones the decision. The juridical language of the heavenly court is precise: <em>gezera</em> (decree/sentence), <em>petagam</em> (word/decision), <em>shuʾalta</em> (request/demand). The heavenly council issues binding decisions about earthly kingdoms. The stated purpose: <strong>di-ydaʿ chayya di-shalit ʿilaya b'malkhut anasha</strong> (that the living may know that the Most High rules in the kingdom of men) — the theological thesis of Daniel's entire vision of history.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The king asks Daniel to interpret because <em>kol-khakimei malkhuti la yakhlin hodaʿutani peshara</em> (all the wise men of my kingdom could not make known to me the interpretation) — the court wisdom system has failed again (cf. ch. 2). The Aramaic <em>hkhim</em> (wise) is the comprehensive term for the Babylonian learned class. Daniel's superiority is framed in terms of the spirit: <em>ruach elahim qadishim</em> (spirit of holy gods), not superior training or skill.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>Belteshatzar etdahar sha'ah akhat</strong> (<em>bēlṭĕšaṣṣar etdahar šāʿah ḥăḏāh</em>): Belteshazzar was alarmed for a moment. <em>Etdahar</em> (was alarmed/horrified) uses the same root as 4:5 for the king's terror. <em>Sha'ah akhat</em> (one hour/moment) — a brief pause of horror at the vision's meaning. Then the king explicitly invites Daniel's honest report: <em>khezva ve-peshara la yevahalanek</em> (let not the dream or its interpretation trouble you) — the king, for once, wants the truth even if it is about himself.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Daniel's description of the tree restates vv. 10-12 almost verbatim — the repetition is formal, legally confirming the interpretation against the original vision. The Aramaic narrative technique of repetition-for-confirmation appears throughout Daniel: visions are restated (2:31-35 restated in 2:38-44), decrees are restated (3:4-6 restated in 3:10-11). The mirroring of original statement and interpretation signals truthfulness and completeness.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The tree whose branches housed the birds, whose shade sheltered the animals, from whose fruit all flesh was fed: these details are restated in the interpretation to prepare for the application. <em>Kol-beshar mineh yitnezuun</em> (all flesh was fed from it): the universality of Nebuchadnezzar's empire-as-provision is the ground of the judgment — he used what YHWH gave him as if he had made it himself (cf. Ezek 29:3: &ldquo;the Nile is mine and I made it&rdquo;).</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>ant-hu malka</strong> (<em>ʾantāh-hûʾ malkāʾ</em>): it is you, O king. The application is direct and personal. The Aramaic pronoun <em>ant-hu</em> (you-he) is emphatic. The phrase <em>di-revat v'etqefat</em> (who grew great and became strong) mirrors the tree's description exactly — the king is the tree. <em>Ve-riavat rugbak ad-shamayya</em> (and your greatness has reached heaven): the same tower-of-Babel language that described the tree now describes Nebuchadnezzar — the echo is unmistakable.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The watcher's decree restated in summary: cut down the tree, but leave the stump. The connecting purpose (<em>di-shalit ʿIllaya b'malkhut anasha</em>: that the Most High rules in the kingdom of men) appears again — this is the sentence's stated rationale. The threefold repetition of this sentence (vv. 17, 25, 32) in ch. 4 is Daniel's theological drumbeat: all human sovereignty is derivative, conditional, and reversible.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>dena peshara malka</strong> (<em>dĕnāh pišrāʾ malkāʾ</em>): this is the interpretation, O king. The formal announcement of the interpretation. <em>Pigra Ilai et-ot malka rabayta</em> (the decree of the Most High has reached my lord the king): the Aramaic <em>mata</em> (reached) suggests the decree has arrived like a legal document. The king stands under a sentence that has already been issued from the heavenly court — the only question is when it will be executed.</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>v'lak letardoon min anasha</strong> (<em>wĕlāk yṭardûn min-ʾĕnāšāʾ</em>): you will be driven from men. The passive <em>yitardoon</em> (will be driven) uses the divine passive — the same God who issued the decree in the heavenly court will execute it. <em>Im-chayat bara tekhul</em> (you will eat grass like an ox): the animal humiliation described. <strong>shiv'a idanin</strong> (seven times) restated: the duration is fixed. The purpose: <em>di-teda di-shalit ʿIllaya</em> (that you may know that the Most High rules) — the personal, second-person application of the theological thesis.</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>v'di amaru lishbaq ikar shorshohi di ilana</strong> (<em>wĕdî ʾămarû lišbaq ʿiqqar šorĕšôhî dî-ʾîlānāʾ</em>): and as for the command to leave the stump of the tree's roots. The stump-preservation is interpreted as the guarantee of Nebuchadnezzar's restoration: <em>malkhutakh lekhak tiqum</em> (your kingdom will be confirmed for you) after you know that Heaven rules. The Aramaic <em>shamayya shalit</em> (Heaven rules) substitutes Heaven as a circumlocution for YHWH — a reverent substitution also found in the phrase <em>malkut shamayya</em> (kingdom of Heaven) in the NT (Matt 3:2; 4:17).</p>",
    "27": "<p><strong>la-ken malka mashlakhani yishtaveh</strong> (<em>lāhēn malkāʾ mšaḥlĕḥānnî yiqqabal</em>): therefore, O king, let my counsel be acceptable to you. Daniel's exhortation to repentance: <em>peruk khatayak bitzidqah</em> (break off your sins by righteousness) and <em>avatek banot anaya</em> (your iniquities by showing mercy to the poor). The two imperatives (<em>pruk</em> = break off/atone; <em>anay</em> = afflicted/poor) constitute a summary of OT ethics: righteousness and mercy. The conditional hope: <em>hn tihye arokhat shlevtak</em> (perhaps there will be a lengthening of your tranquility) — the judgment may be postponed if repentance occurs.</p>",
    "28": "<p>All this came upon Nebuchadnezzar: the narrative resumes after the interpretation with the bare statement of fulfillment. The Aramaic <em>kol-dena mata</em> (all this came) uses the verb <em>meta</em> (to arrive/come) — the decree from the heavenly court has arrived. The time marker <em>leqets yarkheen tri-eshar</em> (at the end of twelve months) shows the delay: one full year elapsed between the dream/interpretation and the judgment. Daniel's exhortation (v. 27) had been followed — at least temporarily.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>al heikhal malkhuta di-Bavel mehhalekh havah</strong> (<em>ʿal hêḵal malkûṯāʾ dî-bābel mĕhallēk hăwāh</em>): on the palace of the kingdom of Babylon he was walking. The setting of the boast: the roof of the palace, looking over the city. <em>Mihallekh havah</em> (was walking) uses the Aramaic participial construction for ongoing action — he was strolling, luxuriating in the view. The timing — at the end of the twelve months, during a moment of prosperous ease — is the narrative's ironic precision: the judgment falls at the height of complacency.</p>",
    "30": "<p><strong>la-da Bavel rabta di-ana benayit</strong> (<em>hălāʾ dāʾ bābel rabbĕṯāʾ dî-ʾănāh bĕnayit</em>): Is not this great Babylon that I built? The boast contains three claims: <em>ana benayit</em> (I built), <em>livet malkhuta</em> (for the house of the kingdom), <em>bitqef khutsani</em> (by my mighty power). Historical confirmation: Nebuchadnezzar was the greatest builder-king in Babylonian history; the surviving texts of his building inscriptions use nearly identical language (&ldquo;I built Babylon, the great city, my royal residence&rdquo;). The irony is that his own inscriptions confirm the accuracy of the biblical portrait — and their boast is the sin Daniel warned against.</p>",
    "31": "<p><strong>od pithgama b'pum malka</strong> (<em>ʿôḏ millĕṯāʾ bepum malkāʾ</em>): while the word was still in the king's mouth. The immediacy is the literary point: the divine verdict falls before the sentence is finished. The Aramaic <em>bat qal nefal min-shamayya</em> (a voice fell from heaven) — <em>bat qal</em> (daughter of the voice) is the technical term in rabbinic literature for a divine voice from heaven, lesser than prophecy but still authoritative. The voice declares: <em>malkhuta avadat minnakh</em> (the kingdom has departed from you) — a perfect/completed declaration.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The prophetic declaration is immediate and specific: <em>min-anasha tetarad</em> (you will be driven from men), <em>im-chayat bara mevakhak lakh</em> (with the animals of the field your dwelling will be). The threefold repetition of <em>shiv'a idanin</em> (seven times) throughout the chapter has built to this moment of execution. The declarative purpose — <em>di-teda di-shalit ʿIllaya b'malkhut anasha</em> (that you may know that the Most High rules in the kingdom of men) — echoes vv. 17 and 25. The purpose of YHWH's judgment is always revelation.</p>",
    "33": "<p><strong>ba-shetaʿa fulfilled upon Nebuchadnezzar</strong> (<em>beh-šaʿtāʾ millĕṯāʾ sāpat ʿal nĕḇûḵaḏ-neṣṣar</em>): at that very hour the word was fulfilled. The Aramaic <em>ba-shetaʿa</em> (at that hour/moment) is emphatic immediacy — no delay between sentence and execution. The medical symptoms described (<em>min-anasha tetarad, v'asba chaiva yikhul, u-ketal-shamayya yitsatabah</em>: driven from men, eating grass like cattle, his body bathed in the dew of heaven) may reflect the condition known as boanthropy — a psychiatric syndrome documented in ancient Near Eastern medical texts and confirmed by modern case studies.</p>",
    "34": "<p><strong>ulqats yomaya ana nebukhad-netstsar einai lishemayya natlet</strong> (<em>ûliqṣāṯ yômayāʾ ʾănāh nĕḇûḵaḏ-neṣṣar ʿênay lišmayyāʾ nĕṭĕlēṯ</em>): and at the end of the days I, Nebuchadnezzar, lifted my eyes to heaven. The raising of eyes to heaven is the recovery of the rational-and-spiritual faculty: <em>umdaʿi yetuv ʿalai</em> (and my reason returned to me). The first act of restored reason is the praise of YHWH: <em>ulilaiay berakhit</em> (and I blessed the Most High). The verb <em>berakh</em> (bless/kneel) signals worship-posture. The confession that follows: <em>malkhuteh malkhut alam v'shaltehneh im-dar v'dar</em> (his kingdom is an everlasting kingdom and his dominion is from generation to generation) — the same formula as v. 3, now confessed from experience rather than introduced as preface.</p>",
    "35": "<p><strong>v'kol-dayrei arʿa k'la khashiveen</strong> (<em>wĕḵol-dāyĕrê ʾarʿāʾ k'lāʾ ḥăšîḇîn</em>): all the inhabitants of the earth are accounted as nothing. <em>K'la</em> (as nothing/zero) is absolute: compared to YHWH's sovereignty, all earthly inhabitors are nothing. The phrase <em>v'kitsvehteh ʿaved bishemayya uvimdinat arʿa</em> (and he does his will in the host of heaven and among the inhabitants of earth) uses the verb <em>ʿaved</em> (does/makes) — YHWH's will is executed in both the heavenly and earthly realms simultaneously. The rhetorical question <em>v'la-itai man di-yemacher b'yedehheh</em> (there is no one who can stay his hand) closes with absolute unilateral sovereignty.</p>",
    "36": "<p><strong>b'idana dena madaʿi yetub ʿalai</strong> (<em>bizdān dĕnāh maddi ʿalai ytûb</em>): at the same time my reason returned to me. The restoration formula is threefold: <em>hadaru heder malkhuti</em> (the majesty of my kingdom was restored), <em>v'labibeday itub lehon</em> (and my reason returned to me), and <em>yattirey revavet</em> (I was greatly increased). The Aramaic <em>hadar</em> (splendor/majesty) is a royal term — the same word used for YHWH's glory in the Psalms (Ps 29:4; 96:6). The restoration of human dignity is described in the same terms as divine glory — another echo of the <em>tselem elahim</em> (image of God) principle.</p>",
    "37": "<p><strong>kaan ana nebukhad-netstsar meshabbech u-meromem umehaddra le-malik shemayya</strong> (<em>kĕʿan ʾănāh nĕḇûḵaḏ-neṣṣar mĕšabbaḥ ûmĕrômem ûmĕhaddêr lĕmelek šemayyāʾ</em>): now I, Nebuchadnezzar, praise and extol and honor the King of Heaven. The triple participle construction (<em>meshabbech, meromem, mehaddra</em> = praising, extolling, honoring) is a liturgical formula — the language of worship applied to YHWH by a Gentile king. The final confession: <em>di-ʿavdeh qeshet</em> (whose works are truth) and <em>urkhev-oteh din</em> (whose ways are justice) — both attributes of YHWH throughout the OT. The closing warning: <em>v'di-mehalkheen begava yakhil le-heshpalah</em> (those who walk in pride he is able to humble) — using the verb <em>yakhil</em> (is able) that the three men used of YHWH's ability to deliver them.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p><strong>Belshatzar malka ʿabad lechem rab</strong> (<em>bēlšaṣṣar malkāʾ ʿăḇaḏ leḥem raḇ</em>): Belshazzar the king made a great feast. Historical note: Belshazzar is now confirmed as a genuine Babylonian figure through the Nabonidus Chronicle and the Verse Account of Nabonidus — he served as co-regent with his father Nabonidus. His title is <em>son</em> of Nebuchadnezzar (v. 2, 11) in the Semitic sense of dynasty-descendant or successor, not literal son. The feast of a thousand: <em>alef rabrevaneh</em> (a thousand of his nobles) — the hyperbolic number of royal grandeur. The historical night is likely October 539 BCE when Cyrus's troops diverted the Euphrates and entered Babylon.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>taam</strong> (<em>ṭĕʿēm</em>): taste/order/edict. The Aramaic <em>taam</em> (taste/judgment/decree) suggests a royal command issued under the influence of wine. The vessels of the Jerusalem temple (<em>mano di-hekhla di-beyt-elaha di-birushalem</em>) are specifically identified: <em>mano</em> (vessels/utensils), <em>hekhla</em> (temple). The desecration of the sacred vessels connects to Nebuchadnezzar's original seizure (Dan 1:2; cf. Ezra 1:7-11) — the vessels taken as war-trophies are now pressed into profane banquet use, escalating the sacrilege.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The active desecration: <em>v'eshtu vahon malka virabrevaneh</em> (and they drank from them, the king and his nobles). The plural includes the concubines and wives (<em>shegalateh unilkhateh</em>). The drinking scene is a deliberate contrast with the earlier narrative: Nebuchadnezzar at least worshipped a god (the gold image); Belshazzar reduces worship to a feast-prop. The vessels become vessels of judgment: what was used to defile becomes the occasion for divine response.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>shabbahu le-elahei dahava vekhaspah</strong> (<em>šabbaḥû lēʾlāhê dahabāʾ wĕḵasp̄āʾ</em>): they praised the gods of gold and silver. The list of six materials (gold, silver, bronze, iron, wood, stone) mirrors the statue of Dan 2 — deliberately invoking Nebuchadnezzar's dream and its interpretation. The six materials correspond to the six kingdoms of the ch. 2 vision. The feast that praises these material gods while desecrating YHWH's temple-vessels is the concentrated expression of what Daniel 2 condemned: human kingdoms that mistake their own material glory for ultimate reality.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>etsba din alaha</strong> (<em>ʾeṣḇāʾ dî yad ʾĕnāšāʾ</em>): fingers of a man's hand. The vision emerges from the wall: <em>ketefat gira di-kedasha di-hechal malka</em> (opposite the lampstand, on the plaster of the wall of the king's palace). The lampstand (<em>nehora</em>, light) illuminates the scene — the writing appears where it can be seen by all. The Aramaic <em>pars khetav</em> (wrote writing) emphasizes both the action and the product: the divine hand writes and the writing stands.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>be-edin malka zivohi shennoi</strong> (<em>bēʾḏayin malkāʾ ziwnôhî šennaw</em>): then the king's countenance changed. The verb <em>shennoi</em> (was changed) is the same root used in 3:19 for Nebuchadnezzar's changed countenance and in 4:16 for the changed heart — Daniel's Aramaic consistently uses this root for radical transformation under divine pressure. <em>Reʾyaneh yevahaloneh</em> (his thoughts alarmed him): the verb <em>behal</em> (to terrify/disturb) appears throughout the chapter (5:9, 10) — the same root as ch. 4's king-in-terror. The physical symptoms — loosened loins, knocking knees — are the diplomatic language for total collapse of composure.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Belshazzar cries out for the same <em>ashpaya vegadzraya khaldaya</em> (astrologers, Chaldeans, diviners) who have failed in every previous crisis (chs. 2, 4). The reward offered is: <em>arganev-an talbash v'hemnikhta di-dahava al-tzawareh</em> (clothed in purple and a chain of gold around his neck) and <em>telita b'malkhuta ishalat</em> (third ruler in the kingdom) — consistent with Belshazzar's position as co-regent: he can only offer <em>third</em> place, not second. This is historically precise and archaeologically confirmed.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The failure of the wise men: <em>la yakhallin khetava lemeqra</em> (could not read the writing) or give interpretation. The Aramaic structure parallels ch. 2 and ch. 4 — the court wisdom system fails identically each time. The literary pattern says: there is a category of knowledge that human wisdom systems cannot access. <em>Peshara lehodat</em> (to make known the interpretation) — the verb <em>ydaʿ</em> (to know/make known) is the epistemological key: Babylonian wisdom cannot produce the knowledge YHWH alone gives.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>be-edin malka Belshatzar saggi metvahel</strong> (<em>ʾeḏayin malkāʾ bēlšaṣṣar saggî mĕṯbahal</em>): then King Belshazzar was greatly troubled. The superlative <em>saggi</em> (greatly) intensifies the already-intense verb. <em>Zivohi shannyin ʿalohay</em> (his countenance was changing upon him) — again the root <em>shannyi</em>. <em>V'rabrevaneh metvahalin</em> (and his nobles were troubled) — the fear spreads from the king to the court. The banquet that began with triumph ends in terror: the vessels of YHWH have become the vessels of judgment.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>malketa liqbel milei malka v-rabrevaneh leveyt mishtaya ʿalit</strong> (<em>malkĕṯāʾ liqbēl millê malkāʾ wĕrabrĕwānôhî lĕḇêṯ mišĕtāyāʾ ʿāllat</em>): the queen, because of the words of the king and his nobles, came into the banqueting hall. The queen who enters is likely the queen-mother — Nitocris or a senior queen with knowledge of Nebuchadnezzar's court (v. 11: &ldquo;in the days of your father&rdquo;). Her composure — <em>malketa lealam kheyey</em> (O king, live forever) — contrasts with the general alarm. She has information the current court lacks.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>itai gever b'malkhutakh di-ruach elahim qadishim beh</strong> (<em>ʾîṯay gĕḇar bĕmalkûṯāk dî-rûaḥ ʾĕlāhîn qaddîšîn bēhî</em>): there is a man in your kingdom in whom is the spirit of the holy gods. The queen-mother's testimony establishes Daniel's credentials by reference to Nebuchadnezzar's own evaluation. Three terms are used for Nebuchadnezzar's recognition of Daniel: <em>nahor</em> (light/illumination), <em>sekhlet</em> (insight), and <em>khokhmat elahim</em> (wisdom of the gods) — the same terms appear in the original court examination (1:20). The spirit that was present in Nebuchadnezzar's day is still present in Daniel: divine gifts are permanent, not generational.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>ruach yatira v'mandaʿ v'sekhlet lefeysher khelmin</strong> (<em>rûaḥ yattîrāh ûmandaʿ ûśokletānû lĕp̄ašar ḥelmîn</em>): an extraordinary spirit and knowledge and understanding to interpret dreams. The list of Daniel's abilities: interpreting dreams, solving riddles (<em>mefesha udah</em>), and loosening knots (<em>meshare qatrein</em>). The Aramaic <em>qatrein</em> (knots/difficulties) is a vivid metaphor for complex problems — the same image appears in modern Arabic. Daniel's name is given by the queen: <strong>Belteshatzar</strong> (his court name) — she uses it to identify him to a king who may not have known him personally.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Daniel is brought before the king. The king's address begins with a biographical note: <em>ant-hu Daniel di-min-benei galuta di-yehud</em> (are you Daniel who is from the exiles of Judah?). The identification of Daniel as an exile (<em>galuta</em>) is politically precise: he has no natural power-base, no dynastic claim, no court loyalty by birth. His status as exile makes his authority all the more clearly supernatural. The king knows Daniel's origin — this is not ignorance but the beginning of an interrogation designed to assess reliability.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The king's statement of what he has heard about Daniel: <em>v'shemet ʿalakh di ruach elahim bakh</em> (and I have heard of you that the spirit of God is in you). The king uses <em>elahim</em> (God/gods) without qualification here — a more personal phrasing than the queen-mother's <em>elahim qadishim</em> (holy gods). The three-part description of Daniel's gifts: <em>nahor v'sekhlet v'khokhmat yatira</em> (light and understanding and excellent wisdom) is identical to the queen's formulation in v. 11. Belshazzar has received the testimony accurately.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The narrative irony is made explicit: the wise men and astrologers who were brought in could not read the writing or make known the interpretation — <em>v'peshara la-yekholeen le-hodat</em>. The Aramaic <em>la-yekholeen</em> (could not) uses the same root (<em>yakhil</em>) that the three men used for YHWH's ability (3:17) and that Nebuchadnezzar used in his final doxology (4:37). The wise men lack the ability that YHWH possesses and grants to his servants.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>v'enant shemaʿet ʿalakh di-tukhhal pishrin lemifsar</strong> (<em>wʾănāh šĕmaʿet ʿălāk dî tûḵal pišrîn lĕmip̄sar</em>): and I have heard of you that you can give interpretations. The conditional invitation: <em>kean hn tukhhal khetava lemeqra</em> (now if you can read the writing). The offer is repeated: purple, gold chain, third-ruler status. The political offer remains operative even after the wise men have failed — Belshazzar is desperate enough to offer the same package to anyone who can succeed.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>be-edin Daniel enah umreh qodam malka</strong> (<em>bēʾḏayin dāniyyēʾl ʿānēh wĕʾāmar qŏḏām malkāʾ</em>): then Daniel answered and said before the king. Daniel's response opens with a formal refusal of the gifts: <em>matnetak lakh yehavu v'yahavatakh le-akhra hab</em> (your gifts be for yourself, give your rewards to another). This is a striking posture: Daniel refuses payment before delivering the interpretation, ensuring his independence from the court system. The interpretation will not be shaped by the reward — a principled stance that contrasts with the court wise men whose interpretations followed the money.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>anta malka elaha ilaya malkhuta v-revuta v-iqqara v-hadar yahav le-nebukhad-netstsar avukh</strong> (<em>ʾantāh malkāʾ ʾĕlāhāʾ ʿelyāʾ malkûṯāʾ wĕrəḇûṯāʾ wʾiqqārāʾ wĕhaḏārāʾ yĕhab lĕnĕḇûḵaḏ-neṣṣar ʾăḇûhāk</em>): you, O king — God Most High gave Nebuchadnezzar your father kingship and greatness and glory and majesty. The fourfold listing (<em>malkuta, revuta, iqqara, hadar</em> = kingship, greatness, honor, glory) uses all the royal-dignity vocabulary of Daniel. The attribution to God Most High (<em>elaha ilaya</em>) establishes immediately that Nebuchadnezzar's power was gift, not achievement — the ground for Belshazzar's guilt in v. 22.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>min-qdam revuteh di-yahav leh kol-amayya umevaya ulishanaya hayu zaʿin v-daylin</strong> (<em>min-qŏḏam gəḇûrəṯēh … kol-ʿammayyāʾ ûmĕʾayyāʾ wĕliššānayyāʾ</em>): before his greatness that he gave him, all peoples, nations, and languages trembled and feared before him. The triadic formula of peoples-nations-languages appears again (cf. 3:4; 4:1) — the scope of Nebuchadnezzar's terror was universal. <em>V-di hava tsave haval</em> (and whom he willed he killed): the absolute power is described without euphemism. This absolute power was YHWH's gift — which makes its abuse in Belshazzar all the more culpable (v. 22).</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>v-kivat levaveh v-ruaheh itkeshiat lihzada</strong> (<em>wûkḇar libbēhî wĕrûḥēhî tiqĕp̄at lĕhazāḏāʾ</em>): and when his heart was lifted up and his spirit became proud. The Aramaic <em>kevat</em> (hardened/stiffened) of the heart is a strong image — the heart becomes rigid, inflexible. The verb <em>tikhep</em> (became strong/proud) uses the same root as <em>tikhep</em> in the tree-image (&ldquo;became strong,&rdquo; 4:11) — Nebuchadnezzar's strength became Nebuchadnezzar's pride, and now it is the cause of his fall. The parallel to Belshazzar makes the typological point: the pattern of pride-judgment repeats.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Daniel's summary of Nebuchadnezzar's humiliation, echoing ch. 4: <em>min-benei anasha tetarad</em> (driven from among men), <em>levaveh im-chayata shevi</em> (his heart was made like the animals), <em>im-radana manveh</em> (his dwelling was with wild asses). The purpose: <em>di-yidaʿ di-shalit elaha ilaya b'malkhut anasha</em> (that he might know that God Most High rules in the kingdom of men). The theological thesis is restated for the fifth time in chs. 4-5: Nebuchadnezzar learned it the hard way; Belshazzar had the testimony of that lesson and ignored it.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>v-ant bereh Belshatzar la-heshpalat levavakh</strong> (<em>wʾantāh bĕrēhî bēlšaṣṣar lāʾ heš-pālət libbāk</em>): and you his son Belshazzar have not humbled your heart. This is the indictment. The verb <em>heshpalat</em> (humbled) uses the Haphel stem of the root <em>shapel</em> (to be low/humble) — the same root used throughout Daniel for YHWH's ability to humble the proud (4:37). The conjunction <em>kol-qobel di-kol-dena yadaʿta</em> (though you knew all this) makes the guilt inexcusable: unlike the nations who had no testimony, Belshazzar had the full record of Nebuchadnezzar's experience and disregarded it.</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>v-ʿal mar-shamayya hitromamta</strong> (<em>wʾal māraʾ-šemayyāʾ hitrommāmta</em>): and against the Lord of Heaven you have exalted yourself. The verb <em>hitromamta</em> (exalted yourself) uses the Hitpael of <em>ram</em> (to be high) — reflexive self-exaltation against the Lord of Heaven (<em>mar-shamayya</em>, a title for YHWH found only here in Daniel and Ezra 1:2). The three desecrations named: <em>manohi di-veiteh</em> (vessels of his house), <em>veant verabrevanakh shegalatakh v-nilkhatakh shatin bahon</em> (and you and your nobles and wives drinking from them), <em>velilahei kaspa vedahava … shabbacht</em> (and you have praised gods of silver and gold). The triple indictment escalates: desecrating what is holy, using the holy for debauchery, replacing YHWH with material gods.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>min-kodamoh shallikh pasa yada</strong> (<em>min-qŏḏāmôhî šĕliḥ pāsāʾ yādāʾ</em>): from his presence was sent the hand, the palm. The Aramaic <em>pasa</em> (palm of the hand) is specific — not a full hand, just the palm with fingers. <em>Shallikh</em> (was sent) uses the divine passive: God sent it. The writing that was inscribed: <em>kehtava dena resham</em> (this writing was inscribed). The divine authorship of the writing is stated without qualification — the question is only whether anyone can read it.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The inscription: <strong>mene mene teqel ufarsin</strong> (<em>mĕnēʾ mĕnēʾ tĕqēl ûp̄arsîn</em>). These are Aramaic words with multiple semantic registers. <em>Mene</em> is from the root <em>mana</em> (to count/number/assign). <em>Teqel</em> is from <em>teqal</em> (to weigh). <em>Parsin</em> is the plural of <em>peres</em> (half-mina, or to divide) — also a pun on <em>Paras</em> (Persia). The doubling of <em>mene</em> may intensify the meaning (numbered, numbered — it is truly numbered), paralleling the doubled dreams of Genesis (41:32: &ldquo;the dream was doubled because the thing is fixed by God&rdquo;). The inscription can also be read as a set of monetary units (mina, mina, shekel, and half-minas) — devaluing kingdoms in a monetary metaphor.</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>dena peshara milta mene</strong> (<em>dĕnāh p̄išrāh millĕṯāʾ mĕnēʾ</em>): this is the interpretation of the word — mene. <em>Manah elaha malkhutakh v-hashlamah</em> (God has numbered your kingdom and brought it to an end). The verb <em>manah</em> (to number/count) is completed action: it is done, the count is finished. The Hiphil <em>hashlamah</em> (brought to completion/an end) uses <em>shalam</em> — the same root as <em>shalom</em> (peace/wholeness/completeness). The irony: YHWH brings Belshazzar's kingdom to <em>shalom</em> — its complete end, its final state — using the peace-vocabulary.</p>",
    "27": "<p><strong>teqel tqilta b-moznaya v-hishtkakhat khasir</strong> (<em>tĕqēl tĕqîltāh bĕmôznayyāʾ wĕhišṭĕkaḥat ḥassîr</em>): teqel — you have been weighed in the balances and found wanting. The passive <em>tqilta</em> (you were weighed) and <em>hishtkakhat</em> (you were found) both use divine passives. The balance/scale (<em>moznayyah</em>) is the judicial metaphor for divine assessment — cf. Ps 62:9 (men are a breath, in the balances they go up). <em>Khasir</em> (deficient/lacking/wanting): the verdict is not that he is evil but that he is insufficient — his kingdom lacks the weight, the substance, to endure. The moral and political assessment coincide in Aramaic <em>khasir</em>.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>peres peliget malkhutakh</strong> (<em>pĕrēs pĕligat malkûṯāk</em>): peres — your kingdom is divided. The singular <em>peres</em> (divide) now applies to both the monetary unit (half) and the geopolitical act. <em>V-yehivat liMadai u-Pharas</em> (and given to the Medes and Persians): the pun is complete — <em>peres</em> (divide) = <em>Paras</em> (Persia). The kingdom that praised the gods of gold, silver, bronze, iron, wood, and stone (v. 4) is itself divided like a coin. Daniel's interpretation converts three monetary nouns into three judicial sentences: counted, weighed, divided — a complete legal verdict in three words.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Belshazzar's response: he honors Daniel with the purple, chain, and proclamation of third-ruler status — the promised reward (v. 7) is paid even though the interpretation is a death sentence. This is a peculiar detail that rings historically true: the king honors the interpreter despite the interpretation. The Aramaic <em>v-karaz ʿalohi</em> (and they proclaimed concerning him) uses the same verb <em>karaz</em> (herald/proclaim) as the herald in 3:4 — the same word that announced the command to worship the image now announces the elevation of the man who refused to be ruled by the system that image represented.</p>",
    "30": "<p><strong>beh be-leilya qetil Belshatzar</strong> (<em>bêhî balēlyāʾ qĕṭîl bēlšaṣṣar</em>): that very night Belshazzar the Chaldean king was killed. The Aramaic <em>beh be-leilya</em> (that very night) uses the doubled temporal expression for absolute immediacy — the same night, not the next day. <em>Qetil</em> (was killed) is the Peal passive — the simple statement of fact, without dramatic elaboration. The word <em>kasday malka</em> (Chaldean king) is the narrator's final epitaph — he is remembered as a Chaldean king, not as a god-fearer. The historical record: Xenophon's Cyropaedia and Herodotus both mention the capture of Babylon during a night feast.</p>",
    "31": "<p><strong>v-Daryavesh Madaya qabbel malkhuta</strong> (<em>wĕdāryāwēš māḏāʾāh qabbēl malkûṯāʾ</em>): and Darius the Mede received the kingdom. The verb <em>qabbel</em> (received/accepted) — the kingdom passes, not by conquest described dramatically, but by quiet transfer. <em>Bar-shinin shittin u-tarteen</em> (being about sixty-two years old): the specific age is either a historical detail or a number significant for the narrative (sixty-two years after Nebuchadnezzar's accession would correspond roughly to 561 BCE; the narrative would then be ca. 539 BCE, within 22 years). The chapter ends not with Cyrus but with Darius the Mede — the figure around whom the next narrative (ch. 6) will turn.</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "13": "<p><strong>hazeh haveit bechezwe leylaya vaara im-anane shemayya kebar enash ateh vead attiq yomaya matah uqdamoy haytivuhi</strong> (Aramaic): 'I saw in the night visions, and behold, with the clouds of heaven there came one like a son of man, and he came to the Ancient of Days and was presented before him.' The 'one like a son of man' (<em>kebar enash</em>, Aramaic for 'like a human being') in Daniel 7 contrasts with the four beasts (lions, bears, leopards, a terrible beast) that rise from the sea — representing successive human empires. The human figure comes from heaven, not the sea, and receives the dominion the beasts claimed. The NT application (Jesus's self-designation as 'Son of Man' in all four Gospels) is the consistent claim that Jesus is this figure who receives eternal dominion from the Ancient of Days — a claim recognized as divine by the Sanhedrin (Mark 14:62-64).</p>"
  },
  "9": {
    "24": "<p><strong>shivim shavuim nechetach al-amecha vehal ir qadshecha lekale happesha ulehatem chataut velchapper avon ulehavi tsdeq olamim velachtom chazot venavia velimshoach qodesh qodashim</strong>: 'Seventy weeks are decreed about your people and your holy city, to finish the transgression, to put an end to sin, to atone for iniquity, to bring in everlasting righteousness, to seal both vision and prophet, and to anoint a most holy place.' The six infinitives of Dan 9:24 have generated centuries of calculation and debate. The <em>shavuim</em> (weeks/sevens) are most naturally weeks of years (seven-year units), giving 490 years from the decree to rebuild Jerusalem. The six goals — which are systematically soteriological and eschatological — align most naturally with Christ's work: atonement (to finish transgression, atone for iniquity), righteousness (bring in everlasting righteousness), and the end of the prophetic age (seal vision and prophet).</p>"
  }
}

DAN_CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>The book of Daniel is set in the Babylonian exile (605-538 BCE) and narrates the experiences of four young Jewish men under Nebuchadnezzar, Belshazzar, Darius the Mede, and Cyrus of Persia. The historical reliability of Daniel's court settings has been debated (Darius the Mede is unattested by name in Babylonian records; some details seemed anachronistic). The primary critical alternative: Daniel was composed ca. 167-164 BCE during the Maccabean revolt, as <em>vaticinium ex eventu</em> (prophecy after the fact) using the fictional setting of the sixth century. Conservative scholars argue for a sixth century date and understand the Darius question as a secondary title for Cyrus or an otherwise unrecorded official. The book's affinities with the Aramaic of the fifth-fourth centuries and the absence of Greek loanwords that would be expected in a second century BCE composition support an early composition.</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>Daniel 7-12 contains four major apocalyptic visions. The genre of apocalypse (from Greek <em>apokalypsis</em>, unveiling) is characterized by: symbolic or heavenly visions mediated by an angel, disclosure of the heavenly perspective on historical events, periodization of history into fixed sequences, and imminent divine intervention. Daniel is the OT's primary apocalyptic text; its imagery (beasts from the sea, the Ancient of Days, the Son of Man, the four kingdoms) was enormously influential on Jewish and Christian apocalyptic (1 Enoch, 4 Ezra, 2 Baruch, and the NT's Revelation). Jesus's eschatological discourse (Mark 13 and parallels) draws extensively from Daniel, particularly the abomination of desolation (Dan 11:31; 12:11 → Mark 13:14) and the coming of the Son of Man (Dan 7:13 → Mark 13:26).</p>"
  }
}

DAN_CHRIST = {
  "7": {
    "13": "<p>A direct revelation: 'One like a son of man came with the clouds of heaven and came to the Ancient of Days and was presented before him. And to him was given dominion and glory and a kingdom, that all peoples, nations, and languages should serve him; his dominion is an everlasting dominion, which shall not pass away, and his kingdom one that shall not be destroyed.' Jesus's consistent self-identification as 'the Son of Man' throughout the Gospels is a deliberate claim to be this figure — the one who receives from the Ancient of Days the universal, eternal dominion. The ascension is the receiving of this dominion; Pentecost is the beginning of its exercise; the parousia is its final manifestation. The 'Son of Man' claim is Jesus's most characteristic and most Christologically loaded self-designation.</p>"
  },
  "9": {
    "26": "<p>A fulfillment: 'After sixty-two weeks, an anointed one shall be cut off and shall have nothing.' The phrase 'cut off' (<em>yikaret</em>) is the judicial-death vocabulary of Torah (used for capital offenses). The anointed one is cut off not for his own sins (the grammar allows 'and there is nothing to him' or 'but not for himself') — the same pattern as Isa 53:8 ('cut off out of the land of the living ... for the transgression of my people'). Regardless of the precise calculation of the seventy weeks, the Christological core is the same: the anointed one (the Messiah) dies, is cut off, apparently without inheriting anything — and yet this death is the very mechanism by which the six goals of v. 24 are accomplished. The cross is Daniel's predicted event.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "2": "<p>A direct revelation: 'And many of those who sleep in the dust of the earth shall awake, some to everlasting life and some to shame and everlasting contempt.' Daniel 12:2 is the OT's clearest statement of a general resurrection with differentiated outcomes — resurrection to life and resurrection to judgment. Jesus applies this directly to himself: 'The hour is coming when all who are in the tombs will hear his voice and come out, those who have done good to the resurrection of life and those who have done evil to the resurrection of judgment' (John 5:28-29). Christ is the voice that summons from the tombs — the executor of Daniel's two-outcome resurrection — and his own resurrection is the first fruits of what Dan 12:2 prophesied for the final eschatological hour.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    books_data = [
        ('deuteronomy', DEUT_ECHO, DEUT_ORIGINAL, DEUT_CONTEXT, DEUT_CHRIST),
        ('jeremiah', JER_ECHO, JER_ORIGINAL, JER_CONTEXT, JER_CHRIST),
        ('ezekiel', EZEK_ECHO, EZEK_ORIGINAL, EZEK_CONTEXT, EZEK_CHRIST),
        ('daniel', DAN_ECHO, DAN_ORIGINAL, DAN_CONTEXT, DAN_CHRIST),
    ]
    for book, echo_d, orig_d, ctx_d, chr_d in books_data:
        e = load_echo(book)
        merge_echo(e, echo_d)
        save_echo('', e) if False else save_echo(book, e)

        c = load_comm('mkt-original', book)
        merge_comm(c, orig_d)
        save_comm('mkt-original', book, c)

        c = load_comm('mkt-context', book)
        merge_comm(c, ctx_d)
        save_comm('mkt-context', book, c)

        c = load_comm('mkt-christ', book)
        merge_comm(c, chr_d)
        save_comm('mkt-christ', book, c)
        print(f'{book}: all 4 layers written')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
